column1: Join us on December 2 at 11 a.m. for 'Adapting to a COVID World' and hear from UC San Diego experts who will describe how epidemic modeling and data-driven approaches led to the strategies behind UC San Diego’s Return to Learn program. Learn more ⬇️  UC San Diego Biological Sciences November 18::: 2021 at 2:11 PM ·  Join us on Dec. 2 at 11 a.m. for our next Deep Look event: Adapting to a COVID World. As the second anniversary of the start of the COVID-19 pandemic approaches::: along with the specter of outbreaks during the winter season::: the world continues to grapple with uncertainties of the pandemic. Join UC San Diego experts who will describe how epidemic modeling and data-driven approaches led to the strategies behind UC San Diego’s Return to Learn program. Scientists also will discuss the latest research on proteins known as interferons and their promise as anti-viral COVID-19 therapeutics. And finally::: hear from evolutionary biologists about what we’ve learned about disease transmission::: changes from the initial Wuhan virus strain and what these variants could mean for the future of this pandemic. Registration: https://bit.ly/3FKm2PN
Thank you for celebrating 61 years with us this week. Photos by Erik Jepsen #UCSDFoundersDay

“Very early on::: I developed a love for music. I grew up in a difficult home environment but always felt safe when practicing at the keyboard. Music was a creative outlet for me to express things I was too afraid to say in words.  I completed an Associate’s in Piano Performance shortly before I completed a B.S. in Zoology. After graduation::: I found employment in administrative roles. I had financial security but something felt missing. In school::: I’d pass by the music building every day and think about what it would be like to study music. I decided to resign from my job::: gather my savings::: and go on a solo trip to Vienna. I came back from the trip with the decision that I’d apply to music school. I took a year to prepare for auditions and graduated with a B. Mus. in music composition in Toronto four years later.  I then moved to Victoria to pursue my master's. I experienced imposter syndrome and had a rough first semester being far from home; I wanted to give up and not come back after the holidays. After talking to my advisor::: I decided to give it another try. This ended up being a transformative experience personally and professionally. I applied to doctoral programs after but was unsuccessful. I moved back home to Toronto to work on my portfolio before a second round of applications. I got involved in the music community and saw my pieces performed::: co-organized workshops with amazing musicians and submitted my application to UCSD for the 2nd time::: getting admitted to the Composition Ph.D. program in February 2018.  Two weeks after::: I was diagnosed with breast cancer. I went from feeling so much happiness to complete shock and numbness. I felt like I had fallen into a nightmare that I couldn’t wake up from. I went through surgery::: chemotherapy::: radiation therapy::: countless medical appointments and tests. I had to defer my program start date by a year. In the middle of my chemotherapy treatment::: my then-fiancé changed his mind about our future together. It felt like my entire life fell apart: my health::: my partner::: my future plans as I knew them.  During my treatment::: there were many moments where I wanted to stop going to my appointments-\-\ I didn’t want to think or feel anything more. My oncology psychiatrist and my family doctor supported my mental health through these excruciatingly painful times; they reminded me that my Ph.D program at UCSD would be waiting for me at the end of the cancer treatment. After months of crying::: talking::: writing::: and more crying::: I decided I wouldn’t let cancer and a horrible break-up stop me from chasing my dreams of a Ph.D. program at UCSD.  In September 2019::: I came to UCSD and started my Ph.D. program. Despite being from a neighboring country::: I experienced culture shock and needed time to reorient myself to a new environment for the first months here. When things started to feel a little more “settled”::: the global pandemic happened::: and everything turned upside down and inside out. As an international student::: there was additional uncertainty of whether I’d be asked to leave with short notice as schools decided on potential teaching delivery methods of remote-hybrid-in-person. International Students & Programs Office - UC San Diego::: The Hub Basic Needs Center::: and the School of Music have all been supportive and understanding of my circumstances-\-\ I wouldn’t have been able to do the things I do without their support and encouragement!  Fall 2021 marks my third year at UCSD and I’m happy to say that I’ve been able to build towards research ideas that draw from both my zoology and music backgrounds. The professors at Scripps Institution of Oceanography welcomed me into their classes and the music professors - they opened my mind and changed my life. I feel incredibly lucky to have the level of engagement and support that I’ve had from the moment I was accepted.  Being an international graduate student who has gone through serious illnesses::: there are both very challenging and beautiful days. I don’t know if my cancer might come back or if my health will take a sudden downward turn one day; but I do know that right now::: I’m able to pursue my love of learning::: music::: realizing my research ideas::: and coming to UCSD has been one of the best decisions I’ve made."  - Janet Sit (she/her)::: 3rd Year Ph.D. Music Composition Student #TritonStories #InternationalStudentDay Photos by Erik Jepsen

column1: Confused? Have some questions about the Gubernatorial Recall Election? Well::: we're here to help you!  What is a recall? A recall is the process in which voters decide whether or not to remove elected public officials from office. The ballot will ask a yes or no question in reference to the recall. From there::: you must select a replacement candidate if you chose::: yes.  From there::: depending on the results::: the elected officer may be removed from office and replaced or remain in office and continue their duties.  To learn more visit ucsd.turbovote.org or sdvote.com.

column1: "Being the eldest of four siblings – all from different generations – and the first child of immigrant parents comes with its challenges and unique celebrations.  I wanted absolutely all the amazing experiences for my siblings. I wanted their journey to achieving their goals and their hearts’ desires to be easier than mine. Going away for college::: even if it was in the same big city::: had a larger effect on my family than I thought it would. This stuck with my youngest sibling::: my mini-me.  When I started as a student at the University of California::: San Diego::: my youngest sister was turning five years old. Leaving home wasn’t easy on anyone. Every time I came home::: I’d bring little gifts for my siblings. The first was a shirt that said::: “My Big Sister Goes to UC San Diego”.  She remembers visiting me on campus::: making friends with mine::: and helping the Muslim Student Association during Justice in Palestine Week. 🇵🇸 She knows all my stories of MSA events and being a founding member of SJP UCSD::: and spending all my time at the Cross Cultural Center. She was excited to hear about all of it.  This little one grew up strong and beautiful.  Last Saturday::: 15 years after I called UCSD my home::: I returned back to campus to give my little sister a tour as the newest Triton! 💛🔱💙 She carried the tiny shirt::: that now only fits on her arm::: with her. We both jumped for joy at her new chapter in education.  I’m so proud of her journey! May Allah swt bless all your future endeavors::: Bara’ah! ❤️ "  - Haneen Oriqat::: Class of '10 (she/her/hers) Featuring her sister Baraah Oriqat::: Class of '23 (she/her/hers)  Our #TritonStories series features personal interviews with members of the UC San Diego community. DM us with your story if you’d like to be featured.

column1: Our campus is leading a new nation-wide AI research institute funded by a $20 million investment from the National Science Foundation (NSF). The Institute for Learning-enabled Optimization at Scale (TILOS) will pursue foundational breakthroughs at the nexus of AI and optimization::: transforming chip design::: robotics::: and communication networks.  UC San Diego Jacobs School of Engineering July 29::: 2021 at 8:53 AM ·  A big win for UC San Diego! Our campus is leading a new nation-wide AI research institute funded by a $20 million investment from the National Science Foundation (NSF). The Institute for Learning-enabled Optimization at Scale (TILOS) will pursue foundational breakthroughs at the nexus of AI and optimization::: transforming chip design::: robotics::: and communication networks.  The Institute will be housed at the Halıcıoğlu Data Science Institute::: UC San Diego's campus hub for data science and artificial intelligence. The institute will be led by UC San Diego in partnership with Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)::: National University::: University of Pennsylvania::: The University of Texas at Austin::: and Yale University. TILOS is also partially supported by Intel Corporation.  “The TILOS mission is to make today’s impossible optimizations possible::: at scale and in practice:::” said Andrew Kahng::: UC San Diego computer science and electrical engineering professor and TILOS director. “Whether for energy-efficiency::: safety::: robustness or other criteria::: improved optimizations have the potential to bring incalculable benefits to society.”  Learn more about this new TILOS AI research institute: https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/pressrelease/TILOS_announcement

column3: this is great news! You also shared wonderful pictures of a graduate that went viral::: her story was inspiring. Unfortunately::: this kind of story may not happen again. So many of your students will not be returning::: they are extremely stressed and depression has set in. The lack of interest the University has shown for these students is unbelievable. Many of these students come from low income homes or their families have been hit hard due to Covid::: how are they expected to find an apartment at $2:::000 a month::: when their parents are struggling to pay their own rent and their credit score has been severely impacted? Many of these students went and stayed in the dorms last year so they would be guaranteed a room this year::: however they were not issued a room. I find it very difficult to watch the University post optimistically when their students are struggling with the stress from not having housing. I believe the University needs to take a hard look at what is important::: these students did not have a senior year of high school::: they have endured numerous let downs and now the University has crushed them. These students have no option but to drop and with no time left many will not be able to attend any school in fall. It is absolutely devastating and the reality of the situation is those who will be hardest hit will come from low income homes. Please take a hard look at the situation and realize you have negatively impacted these students future. Open up the dorms::: give these students an opportunity to obtain the education at the University they worked so hard to be accepted into.

column1: UCSD Geisel Library will safely reopen the 1st and 2nd (main) floors for quiet::: individual study on June 29. Visitors must have their campus ID and show their health screening (employees) and green thumb (students) at entry. About 300 study seats are available with Mac and PC computers::: no reservations required.  Geisel Library hours will be Sunday through Friday from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Library services are not available::: including access to collections and group study rooms. All other Library buildings and all Library service desks remain closed at this time.  Then on September 7::: the Biomedical Library Building will fully reopen followed by Geisel’s full reopening on September 13 for UC San Diego students::: faculty::: staff and the general public. In-person services will resume and access to physical spaces will be expanded.  For more info: https://bit.ly/2SUOknK  Photo by @linearcurvature

For more information and to livestream the event: commencement.ucsd.edu #UCSD2021

“As a high schooler::: my parents told me that the only way I was going to be able to understand how important it was to pursue a higher education was to work as a migrant field worker. My parents came from Michoacan::: Mexico and were not fortunate enough to live their dreams of pursuing a higher education and obtaining the dream career they desired.  When I first started working in the fields::: I would get off from school::: straight to cross country practice::: run miles and miles and then get picked up by my dad to go work in the fields overnight. We would plant strawberries::: get off at around 2-3 am and wake up at 5am to get ready::: or else I would miss the city bus. I admired the workers because they kept working despite backaches while flies::: mosquitos::: and bugs kept roaming their faces::: getting into their eyes. Nobody thinks about nor sees what happens behind a vegetable you grab at the grocery store. But behind it is someone who breaks their backs every day working in the fields.  I continued working in the fields even after I had left for college on weekends or on breaks even though I had a job with UCPD. I wasn’t able to dorm at school because my parents couldn’t afford it::: so I had to commute from far distances like Oceanside and Lakeside. Having to work two jobs::: commute::: and go to school at the same time was a struggle. Many times I wanted to give up::: but my parents and their pieces of advice and support were the reason I kept going.  If it wasn’t for how my parents raised me I don’t know who I would be today. Coming from a field worker background has motivated me to work hard as my parents took my sisters and I to the fields in order to understand how difficult labor is.  Working in the fields builds and molds a different type of character. A character that does not give up::: and one with resilience and strength to withstand the hazards that come from that job.”  -Jennifer Rocha ‘21 (@jrocha_10) B.A. Sociology - Law and Society::: Muir College  Our #TritonStories series features personal interviews with members of the UC San Diego community. Photo by @branden.shoots

column139: I did not understand the immense value of the ethics and physicality of the farm laborer..... that was until I became an apartment manager at a low income farm labor community. Dinner is ready. Clothes go into the washers at the laundry mat (sometimes barely dry by closing).... to turn and leave at day light to do work no one else will do. And yet::: with love::: so many gifted me fresh berries::: veggies::: Christmas trees::: their desserts::: breads and traditional foods. One even had woven a fabric and made me a traditional dress. I was so honored. Eventhough we couldn't communicate easily with language we had a trust and a strong friendship. They taught me so much about their culture::: their lives::: their love and their losses but I always knew I was safe with them. I thanked them often for the work they did. I wanted them to know I understood it was not easy and if they wanted to work in a different field and was able to qualify I would do anything I could to help them. Bless all of those farm laborers. column436: As Americans::: every single one of us owe a debt of gratitude so large we could never repay it::: to the migrant workers who work in 110° heat::: with no benefits and poverty wages::: and in many places with not so much as a restroom to use during their day in the fields. This is the kind of work that destroys the back::: tortures the hands::: wears the knees and the pay they received is totally dependent on the amount of crop they are able to harvest::: so there is no downtime. And then they have to live on the outskirts of communities where the people who eat the food that they harvest look at them with disdain::: who want them to disappear at the end of the day when they're done with their backbreaking labor to feed us::: who don't give a damn about the toll that this physical work and exposure to chemicals that will alter these people's lives and possibly hasten their deaths. I stand with migrant farm workers. Si se puede! ✊

column1: Commencement is just 9 days away! If you haven't taken your graduation photos::: here are six photography tips and photos from UC San Diego student and photographer @photoswithsravya 📸  1. Explore San Diego when looking for new places to shoot! Torrey Pines Gliderport is an awesome location to shoot at with its breathtaking ocean views::: and some other favorite spots include Sunset Cliffs and Balboa Park.  2. Don't be afraid of overcast or gloomy weather when shooting. It actually provides great::: even lighting::: smooths out skin tones::: and the foggy look is a great touch at the beach!  3. Take pictures during golden hour! The key is to have your subject facing away for great backlit lighting. You'll get an angelic but warm glow to your photos that you definitely don't want to miss.  4. Florals and greenery provide a stunning bokeh in portrait shots::: especially when they match a color in your subject's hair or outfit! You can find some at Muir College or the Challenge Course.  5. Shoot wide! Geisel Library is architecturally stunning::: and shooting with a wide-angle lens can allow you to capture all of its details.  6. Many photographers say to not shoot in harsh light. However::: the key is to have your subject directly facing the light and tilt their head up to avoid any harsh shadows!

The UC San Diego community is remembering Chancellor Emerita Marye Anne Fox::: who passed away this weekend. As UC San Diego’s seventh chancellor::: Fox was the first woman to be appointed as permanent chancellor. She led the university during a historic era of extraordinary campus growth and through unprecedented financial challenges. Under her leadership::: UC San Diego successfully completed a billion-dollar capital campaign::: celebrated its 50th anniversary::: and expanded the campus at a record pace to accommodate student growth and a billion-dollar research enterprise. UC San Diego would not be where it is today without her visionary leadership and steady hand.  ADMINRECORDS.UCSD.EDU In Memoriam: Chancellor Emerita Marye Anne Fox

column4: Some of the content of the letter::: from the classes to the recipients: Our wishes for you are that…. You remain safe::: healthy::: and happy; that the coming months treat you well and that you are able to move beyond the challenges you’ve endured in recent times; that you find joy and light::: even in situations that are less desirable; that you make the most of these socially-distan ced days; that you live a fulfilling life surrounded by people who love and appreciate you; that you enjoy every moment as if it were your last; that you show love to the people you care about; that you dream about the future::: and are safe and healthy in every fashion; that you take time in your day to listen to your favorite tunes (we love to listen to music to lift our spirits and recall memories associated with particular songs); that you have all of your physical and psychological needs met; that you feel connected to others; that you feel seen::: heard::: valued and cherished; that you are able to share your story and never be forgotten; that future generations learn from you and right the wrongs of the past; that you get to smile about something every day; that you feel accepted::: comforted::: encouraged::: protected::: respected::: supported::: connected::: safe and most of all::: that you feel loved::: even when you are alone ❤️. And our wishes for the world are that… We can get everyone vaccinated soon; that people overcome their differences so we can make progress; that we are all more empathetic and understanding of one another; that we all take every opportunity to learn about something new and grow; that there be greater peace and unity among us all☮.

No temperature but after a night of sleep::: waking up with chapped lips like one that was running a fever::: now for weeks dehydrated and exhausted.  -\-\ -  Just like with staphylococcus::: covid-19 might have the same qualities.  Remember sometimes a virus can "hide" even after you have knocked it out and feel all better. Part of the reasoning to stay the full course of treatment in cases of staphylococcus.  -\-\ -  Perhaps with the coronavirus of 2019 a treatment plan needs to be in place after the infected individual starts feeling better just as with a major staphylococcus infection to eliminate a flair up from a taxing stress to ones systems creates a mutation. column1: Zoom your way into the holiday spirit with our latest background ☃️

Just arrived! The UC San Diego Health Pharmacy team just unpacked the first shipment of Pfizer-BioNtech COVID-19 vaccine::: moving the doses into storage in -80 freezers::: in an area they call the “Freezer Pharm.”  "These are momentous days::: though too often darkened by rising rates of COVID-19 transmission::: reports of overstressed hospitals::: increasing sickness and mortality. But now::: we are in a moment::: one infused with hope. We are turning a corner: the beginning of the end of the pandemic.⁠” - Patty Maysent::: CEO of UC San Diego Health  UC San Diego Health December 15::: 2020 at 12:10 PM ·  Just arrived! We received the first shipment of the COVID-19 vaccine this morning.⁠  "These are momentous days::: though too often darkened by rising rates of COVID-19 transmission::: reports of overstressed hospitals::: increasing sickness and mortality. But now::: we are in a moment::: one infused with hope. We are turning a corner: the beginning of the end of the pandemic.  This week::: the first allocation of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine arrived at UC San Diego Health::: just as similar shipments are appearing across the country. The first inoculations at UC San Diego Health are slated to begin this week as well.  Per guidance for the Centers for Disease Control::: Food and Drug Administration and public health experts::: these first doses will go to health care workers at UC San Diego Health who are deemed at greatest risk of exposure to COVID-19::: such as emergency department staff::: critical care staff::: trauma staff::: respiratory therapists and personnel with face-to-face patient care in urgent care clinics.  Our goal is to vaccinate as many employees as quickly as possible::: depending upon supplies and evolving circumstances. With subsequent vaccine shipments from Pfizer and as other vaccines::: such as Moderna::: come online::: we will expand the opportunity to vaccinate to all health system employees::: our patients and communities beyond. We are determined to do this as safely and effectively::: as rapidly and methodically::: as we can.  But even with actual vaccinations starting::: we must continue to follow all current measures designed to slow viral spread and infection::: from masking and distancing to hand washing and signing up for #CANotify.  Some may ask why rush to vaccinate if these other measures are working. The simple answer is that they are only partial measures; the only way to completely end this pandemic is to widely distribute safe::: effective vaccines::: minimizing the costs to society::: already so dear.  To that end::: we have begun." - Patty Maysent::: CEO::: UC San Diego Health  #UCSDCares💙 #EndCOVID19 #InThisTogetherSD #UCSDHealth

This is a win for DACA recipients::: their families::: and for this country that has been so enriched by immigrants.  Meanwhile::: Congress must act on comprehensive reform that addresses our country's broken system and recognizes the full contributions of immigrant communities in America."  University of California President Michael V. Drake::: M.D.::: and Board of Regents Chair John A. Pérez::: issued the above statement today following Judge Nicholas G. Garaufis’s decision to order the full reinstatement of the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program. Due to the efforts of UC and many others::: the Supreme Court in June held that the administration’s attempt to rescind DACA was arbitrary and capricious. Rather than reinstate DACA in full::: however::: the administration sought to cut back on DACA and its benefits.

column1: With approximately 18 American Indian reservations::: the County of San Diego has more Indian reservations than any other county in the United States. UC San Diego's Intertribal Resource Center was established by the university in response to a student movement that called for stronger presence and awareness of Native Americans::: as well as other underrepresented groups::: on campus. column6: Celebrate Central Library's 50th Anniversary with your memory.  As I awakened in the UCSD eucalyptus forest in 1970::: of a year long “Live in My Earth Art” project::: I glanced over at my companion I watched birth and grow into a longtime future friend…Central Library. From those first months watching Central Library’s concrete fingers reaching skyward like two hands poised to receive whatever the universe bestowed on our campus::: to the night the interior lights switched on like a star bright engagement ring promising a future together forever. Stowing my sleeping bag in my makeshift camp I strolled to meet fellow fencing team captain and future science fiction writer Kim Stanley Robinson at the Winnie Memorial for a morning coffee and conversation about what UCSD’s future might hold. We laughed at the title “Central Library” because it rose up deep in the forest at the farthest point north of our young campus. Kim asked how many nights I scrambled in from the rain to sleep under the library’s double umbrella like design. We both gazed down at the smoke stain outline of George Winnie burned into the terracotta tiles pondering how long he will be remembered when the library completes its growth to become the center of our campus.

column1: In 1951::: scientists took a black woman's cancer cells without her consent. Henrietta Lack's cells proved invaluable for research::: and labs and companies gained financially from using them for decades::: with nothing for her or her family. Recently::: UC San Diego Biological Sciences and UC San Diego School of Medicine graduate student Donte Alexander Stevens::: postdoctoral fellow Jenna Chistensen and professor Samara Reck-Peterson took action to address the issue. Stevens said the idea that the lab should do something was born out of conversations after the civil unrest following the killing of George Floyd in May. “Racism is everywhere:::” Stevens said. “It got us thinking about how racism affects science.”  WSJ.COM WSJ News Exclusive | Henrietta Lacks and Her Remarkable Cells Will Finally See Some Payback

column1: Last night::: the university was made aware of an Instagram account posting hateful::: racist content. We firmly denounce what was shared on this account that claimed affiliation with UC San Diego::: and condemn all forms of racism and hate. We understand a similar account posted::: claiming affiliation with another university. The Office for the Prevention of Harassment and Discrimination (OPHD) is working with our Chief Information Security Officer to investigate the incident.  If anyone has information about the creator of this account::: please contact our Office for the Prevention of Harassment and Discrimination at OPHD@ucsd.edu. If found that UC San Diego community members are involved::: they will be held accountable. UC San Diego stands with our Black community members and firmly against all forms of racism and hate.  We encourage our community to actively counter racist speech and to be an ally and advocate to any group that is harmed::: by upholding UC San Diego's Principles of Community and our commitment to each other as Tritons.

column3: China's new Hong Kong national security law expands across the world  It is not just Hongkongers who are affected by the new so-called national security law. According to China::: it's everyone in the world.  Article 38 says that this Law shall apply to offenses committed against #HongKong from outside the region by a person who is NOT a permanent resident of Hong Kong.  And article 29 says that people who “provoke hatred” towards the Chinese regime or Hong Kong government could be given a life sentence.  Therefore this law affects not only Hong Kong residents::: the 80:::000 American citizens::: or the 30:::000 UK citizens living in the region... But even foreigners who live outside of Hong Kong can be charged for things like speaking at a pro-Hong Kong rally::: writing an op-ed article criticizing Beijing::: or pushing for sanctions against China.  Such people are at risk if they travel to #China or simply transfer flights in Hong Kong. Experts say the law is even broader than China’s own criminal legislation. column1: Juneteenth celebrates the end of slavery in the U.S. On June 19::: 1865::: Major General Gordon Granger arrived in Galveston::: TX and announced the end of the Civil War and slavery. However::: the Emancipation Proclamation came two years earlier on January 1::: 1863. Many enslavers continued to hold enslaved people captive after the announcement::: so Juneteenth became a symbolic date representing African American freedom. California celebrates #Juneteenth as a day to honor and reflect on the significant role that African Americans have played in the history of the U.S. and how they have enriched society through their steadfast commitment to promoting unity and equality.  Photo by Erik Jepsen of the UC San Diego Visual Arts Black Lives Matter mural designed and painted by 3B Collective::: Oscar Magallanes and other MFA students.

column9: I wish this had posted two days ago::: rather than an hour before the ceremony began. I also wish the manner of the broadcast had been more clearly spelled out. Drop down menus led me to believe there were still two ceremonies as different times were indicated for each college. I even emailed the commencement email address for clarification of how to access the stream and the replies did not set me up to anticipate what actually transpired this morning. I am grateful we were able to connect and watch::: but I am pretty sure I gave all of our family poor instructions based on my email correspondence with UCSD. I wish you had let a parent be in charge of communication. I think the university had much on its plate and given the odd circumstances::: I presume a parent with personal interest could have better directed the university towards clearer commencement communications and possibly also avoided the regalia debacle. I am trying to keep perspective::: but I would be lying if I didn’t share how much I was craving the tiny bit of pomp a UCSD stole would have added to my graduate’s day. I don’t know if it was a university blunder or a Josten’s blunder::: but not being able to order regalia on line from March-May (and then doing so by the announced may 15th date and still not receiving purchased items by today’s virtual graduation) was really short sighted of whomever made that call to suspend ordering. Thanks anyway for the effort to produce the virtual graduation. Something was better than nothing. Congratulations to the Class of 2020!

A Message to Black Faculty::: Staff and Students from University Leadership  "We condemn the racist and unjust rhetoric and actions that have resulted in more attacks on Black Americans. We honor freedom of expression and encourage our campus community to exercise their inalienable rights through peaceful protests and civil discourse to counter hate and injustice. In protesting for basic human rights and seeking justice for those whose rights are violated::: you are demonstrating UC San Diego values. We stand together in solidarity with you and affirm our collective commitment to liberty and justice for all."  ADMINRECORDS.UCSD.EDU A Message to Black Faculty::: Staff and Students

column4: You all lied to me in April 2013. One of your Radiologists diagnosed Superior Mesenteric Artery Syndrome and the other doctors continued to call me a liar and drug seeker::: even in the doctors notes. You all kicked me out of E.R.s repeatedly without stabilizing me::: told paramedics I was "using them.as a taxi when her husband's on duty"::: had nurses draw blood and trash it in front of me::: flagged me out of being able to go to other E.Rs and then::: and only then::: did I finally give up and try to end it all myself. When I FINALLY ended up in palliative care::: going from 133 to 62lbs::: it was ONLY because the PICC line you all made me use got infected when all I was allowed for pain management was hot showers and heating pads when::: low and behold::: my heart was crushing my stomach shut the whole time. All of a sudden::: the Cyclic Vomiting Abortive Therapy worked and I did have Superior Mesenteric Artery Syndrome and needed a feeding tube. In my death bed. Now it's happening again::: but because you saw me alone from the effects of this on my marriage as well::: you all even said "Why did you come to us?" Because this was where I was being helped. I'm not letting this go this time.

UNIVERSITYOFCALIFORNIA.EDU University of California Board of Regents unanimously approved changes to standardized testing requirement for undergraduates  University of California May 21::: 2020 at 2:49 PM ·  This just in: The UC Board of Regents unanimously approved the suspension of the standardized test requirement (ACT/SAT) for all freshman applicants until fall 2024. The suspension will allow the University to create a new test that better aligns with the content the University expects students to have mastered for college readiness. However::: if a new test does not meet specified criteria in time for fall 2025 admission::: UC will eliminate the standardized testing requirement for California students. For more information::: visit: https://bit.ly/2ysfRTo
